Release Detection
1.Chlorine monitor / detector;
2.Monitors in Control House;
3.Plant staffing and on call personnel 24 hours per day;
4.Additional staffing for material handling operations during daylight hours.

Release Containment/Control 
1.Process relief valves to prevent catastrophic release from inadvertent overpressure;
2.Valves to permit isolation of the materials from potential leaks;
3.Building enclosure to contain releases and reduce community impact;
4.Redundant equipment and instrumentation. 

Release Mitigation
1.Fire suppression and extinguishing systems for Chlorine building;
2.Coordinated Emergency Response program with local and County emergency responders; 
3.Personal protective equipment including self-contained breathing apparatus worn during chlorine tank exchange;
4.Tight building enclosure for Chlorine.

i-6.3  Prevention Program Summary
The WTP has taken the necessary steps to comply with the accidental release prevention program requirements set forth under OSHA, EPA and State process safety regulations. The following sections briefly describe the elements of the release prevention program that are in place.

